Is there a black box in your car?
While American road designers are trying to find money to repair a crumbling highway system, many are beginning to see the solution in a small black box neatly attached to the dashboard of your car.
These devices, which track every mile a motorist drives and relay that information to officials, are at the center of a contentious effort to modernize America’s outdated highway financing system by the planning agencies of Washington and the state.
Usually, the boring planning arena of highways has suddenly given rise to intense debates and colorful alliances.
Libertarians have joined environmental groups in lobbying to give the government the right to use small boxes to track the number of miles you drive and even possibly where you drive them — and then use that information to compile tax returns.
The tea party is in shock.
The American Civil Liberties Union is also deeply concerned and raises a number of questions about privacy.
And while Congress can’t yet agree whether to continue or not, several states aren’t going to wait.
They are thinking about how, over the next decade, we can move to a system where drivers pay for every mile of the road they drive.
Thousands of motorists have already tested these black boxes, some of which have a satellite tracking function.
This is really necessary for our country.
“It’s not an issue that we can have a choice on,” said Hassan Ihrata, executive director of the Southern California Government Association, which is preparing plans to begin tracking the miles driven by each California motorist by 2025.
There will be changes in how we pay these taxes.
Technology already exists for this.
The need for this is aggravated by the lack of funds from the Government Fund for the Construction of Highways, financed by taxes that Americans pay at gas stations.
Americans don’t buy as much gasoline as they used to.
Cars travel more miles per gallon.
The federal tax itself, 18.4 cents per gallon, has not been raised for 20 years.
Politicians do not want to raise the tax even by one cent at high prices for gasoline.
“The gasoline tax simply cannot be maintained,” said Lee Mannich, a transportation policy expert at the University of Minnesota.
In his state, 500 tracking devices were recently installed on cars to test the system of erroneous payment.
“It will be the best alternative in the long run,” he said.
Bored people call this an erroneous user fee.
Unsurprisingly, this idea appeals to urban liberals, as taxes could change the nature of travel to reduce road congestion and greenhouse gas emissions, for example.
Planners in California are eyeing the system as they develop strategies to meet the targets set by the state’s ambitious global warming laws.
However, Rep. Bill Schuster, a Republican from Pennsylvania, chairman of the House Transportation Committee, said he also sees the system as the most viable long-term alternative.
The free-marketers at Reason are also excited about making drivers pay for every mile.
“It’s not just a tax that will go into a black hole,” said Adrian Moore, vice president of policy at Reason.
People pay directly for what they get.
The movement is also backed by two former U.S. transportation ministers who in 2011 called on Congress to move toward a false payment.
The U.S. Senate approved last year a $90 million pilot project that would have involved about 10,000 vehicles.
However, House leaders rejected the proposal because of fears of rural legislators representing voters, who often have to travel many miles in their daily lives to get to work or to the city.
Several states and cities, however, follow this path on their own.
The greatest enthusiasm is shown in the state of Oregon, where 5,000 drivers are involved in the largest experiment in the country.
These drivers will soon be paying the state for miles of mileage instead of a gasoline tax.
In Nevada, the pilot project has already been completed.
It is under consideration in New York.
Illinois will test it on a limited basis with the participation of trucks.
And the I-95 coalition, which includes the transportation departments of 17 East Coast states (including Maryland, Pennsylvania, Virginia, and Florida), is exploring how they can implement these changes.
This concept has not been universally recognized.
In Nevada, where about 50 volunteer cars were recently equipped with these devices, drivers were concerned that the government could track their every move.
“Worrying about Big Brother and things like that is a big problem,” said Alauddin Khan, head of strategy and performance management at the Nevada Department of Transportation.
It wasn't what people wanted.
When the tests were in full swing, the Nevada branch of the American Civil Liberties Union warned on its website: “It will be very easy to turn these devices into full-scale surveillance devices.”
There is no need to create a huge, cumbersome technological infrastructure that will inevitably expand to store records of the daily movements of individual citizens.
Nevada is one of several states that are struggling to find an inexpensive technology that would allow state authorities to keep track of the miles driven by the car, but without information about the place and time.
If you can do that, Khan said, society will feel more at ease.
The search for this technology led some state agencies to a small young company in California called True Mileage.
Initially, this company was not engaged in assistance in the collection of state taxes.
It sought to enter the emerging market for a type of auto insurance in which drivers pay on the basis of mileage.
But the devices it tests attract road designers because they don’t use GPS and provide a limited amount of information that is periodically downloaded using a modem.
“People will be more likely to do this if you don’t track their speed and track their location,” said Ryan Morrison, CEO of True Mileage.
There have been some big mistakes in some of these state pilot programs.
There are much less expensive and less intrusive ways to do this.
In Oregon, designers are experimenting with giving drivers different options.
They can choose a device with or without GPS.
Or they may abandon the device altogether, opting instead to pay a fixed fee based on the average number of miles all residents of the state drive.
Elsewhere, they hope to sell the idea to a wary public, forcing the devices to do more, not less.
In New York City, transportation officials are seeking to develop a tax-paying device that will also accept parking meter payments, provide “pay as you drive” insurance, and collect a pool of real-time speed data from other drivers that motorists could use to avoid traffic jams.
“Motorists will be attracted to the participation of the benefits that they will be offered”, – stated in the document of urban planning.
Some transport system designers, however, are wondering if all the talk of erroneous payment is just a huge distraction.
In the San Francisco Bay Area city transportation commission, officials say Congress could very easily overcome the bankruptcy of the trust’s Highway Construction Fund by raising taxes on gasoline.
An additional one-time or annual tax could be levied on hybrid car drivers and others whose vehicles don’t use a lot of gasoline to make them pay their fair share.
“There’s no need for radical surgery when all you need to do is take an aspirin,” said Randy Rentschler, director of the Commission on Legislation and Public Relations.
If we do that, hundreds of millions of drivers will worry about their privacy and a lot of other things.
The EU is preparing measures to support Ukraine in case of economic pressure from Russia
The European Union has a contingency plan to provide Ukraine with gas, as well as to reach an agreement with the IMF on an emergency loan, if Russia takes any measures in response to the possible signing of an association agreement between the EU and Ukraine at the Vilnius summit.
The IMF is negotiating a stand-by loan, and another EU official directly involved in the negotiations added that their goal is to conclude an agreement in the near future.
At the same time, in addition to a potential loan from the IMF, Ukraine can receive 610 million euros from the European Union itself.
Analysts polled by Reuters doubt that Ukraine and the IMF are able to overcome long-standing disagreements over funding conditions.
He does not believe in the possibility of reforms necessary to obtain assistance, and the international rating agency S&P, which on Friday lowered the sovereign rating of Ukraine by one step - to "B-" with "B".
However, EU officials say that the IMF can show flexibility in terms of lending, taking into account the circumstances of Ukraine.
In addition to the plan of financial support for the country, the EU has a backup option to provide Ukraine with gas, the vast majority of which now comes from Russia.
Perhaps it will be gas from Nord Stream or reverse from Slovakia.
The latter, according to officials, is the most possible and acceptable way in case Russia “isolates” Ukraine.
Analysts believe that this method of reverse deliveries to Ukraine can be used only for a few weeks, and is likely to lead to a decrease in supplies to other regions.
“Negotiations are underway between EU countries and Ukrainians on how to create favorable conditions so that Ukraine can import gas from other sources, not from Russia, or from the same source, but on other routes,” the source added.
Russia out of the fight for pollution of cities by cars
Attempts to solve the transport problems of large cities have been observed in most megacities of the world since the second half of the twentieth century.
As a rule, it was either about their reorganization and expansion of the highways, or about attempts to reduce the demand for road trips, the number of cars and the time of their use.
A well-known example of Singapore, which introduced a strict quota for the growth of the number of private cars, and the right to purchase them is purchased at auctions.
Its price can be two to three times the price of the car itself.
European cities, including London, have introduced a fee for entry into the city center.
In Germany, for example, in Hamburg and Stuttgart, the so-called green zones are introduced, where only cars with a certain eco-class are allowed to enter, which also use high-quality fuel (including biofuels or electric cars).
Beijing’s Environmental Protection Agency, for example, approved a “five-year clean air plan” in 2012 with a total value of about 250 billion yuan (about $40 billion).
According to Li Kunsheng, director of the Transportation Pollution Control Division of Beijing Municipal Environmental Protection Bureau, the main goal of the five-year plan is to reduce the leading air pollutants by 20-35% by 2017, increase the number of private cars to no more than 6 million (now 5.2 million), and increase the use of fuel per vehicle by no more than 5%.
According to the agency, now motor transport in Beijing is responsible for 22.5% of total air pollution.
Among the main measures of the program is the restriction of the use of road transport, as well as the introduction of additional taxes for car owners.
Among other things, the urban measures of the "green five-year plan" include an accelerated transition to European fuel standards compared to the rest of the country, the introduction of a local system of eco-standards and marking of cars and fuel, a restriction on the entry of cars into the central part of the city, a ban on the use of outdated vehicles (in addition, the creation of public transport and the development of electric vehicles to replace old cars with electric vehicles).
Beijing's automotive innovations also include a ban on all private cars to move within the fifth transport ring (there are six in the capital of China) one day a week (the relevant information is contained in the license plate of the vehicle), as well as the issuance of registration plates for cars based on the lottery (for example, in 2011, the first year of operation of the lottery, the total number of cars in the registration part).
According to the current state program “Environmental Protection for 2012-2020”, the number of cities with high and very high air pollution should be reduced to 128 (in 2012 there were 138).
According to the Ministry of Natural Resources, in 2011 “mobile sources” accounted for 41% of all emissions of pollutants into the atmosphere of cities.
In Moscow, for example, emissions from cars are ten times higher than industrial, and in St. Petersburg - nine times.
Russia is just beginning to think about the possibilities of restrictive regulation of cars on the streets of cities.
Mikhail Blinkin, Director of the HSE Institute of Transport Economics and Transport Policy, believes that administrative and fiscal measures aimed at suppressing the demand for road travel are obviously unpopular, they can be taken by society only if they are fully universal.
In the case of Moscow, there is a unique problem associated with the structure of its fleet, where there are two clusters of weakly sensitive to any regulatory influences - office and personal cars, as well as cars of "privileged" users, the total number of which is at least 200 thousand (about 5% of the total number of Moscow's fleet).
Recently, urbanists from the ECOM center in St. Petersburg prepared a study that analyzes the balance of urban areas between residential development, the area of the road surface and the number of vehicles.
The main findings of the researchers: the city center is provided with roads half as much as required, and most motorists living in the center do not use cars every day, leaving them for a long time in parking lots or just on the streets.
As a result, it is proposed to build not parking lots, but car storages, not to expand, but to reduce the roadway (so that the streets become more pedestrian-friendly), as well as to limit the use and placement of personal transport within the territory of the protection zone of the historical center (a total area of about 3,212 hectares, covering a number of central areas of the city).
