Goldman Sachs warned about the risks to the Russian economy
Goldman Sachs has warned of growing risks to Russia’s main driver of fragile economic growth – consumption.
This is primarily a crisis of non-payment on unsecured consumer loans and mass layoffs of workers.
Our main concern now is not that growth has slowed, but rather the structure of that growth.
Recently, it is entirely due to consumption, which almost does not reduce turnover, ”said the chief economist of Goldman Sachs for Russia, Clemens Grafe, presenting yesterday the quarterly report of the investment bank on the Russian economy.
Now the nominal wage growth in Russia is about 10%.
With an inflation rate of 6%, it will be able to provide future consumer demand at about the current level, Goldman Sachs expects.
But the profitability of Russian companies is falling, so most likely they will be engaged in optimizing personnel costs.
Today we see a significant increase in the share of wages in GDP: if wages grow by 10%, then GDP - only by 2%, - Mr. Grafe explained.
Companies are facing a reduction in profitability.
If it does not grow, it can lead to layoffs and an increase in unemployment.
Russian business can not not raise wages, comments the chief economist of Barclays Capital for Russia and the CIS Vladimir Pantyushin.
Unemployment near historic lows, competition for workers is high.
To lure employees away or keep current ones, employers have to raise wages.
Consumption in Russia is supported by a very rapid growth in demand for credit.
According to Mr. Grafe, due to the extremely high rates on consumer loans, this type of lending does not have a multiplier effect on the country's economy.
“We have not seen any benefits for the economy from the growth of lending, money does not diverge across the economy, but returns to the same banks in the form of interest payments,” the economist said.
But the problem is the other - Goldman Sachs expect an increase in late payments on unsecured loans.
They are taken mainly by poor people who have nothing to provide.
The interest rates on these loans are high.
As a result, they are often not returned,” said Mr. Grafe.
Therefore, the second threat to economic growth in Russia is a possible crisis of non-payment on unsecured loans.
Vasyl Solodkov, Director of the HSE Banking Institute, is already seeing signs of an impending banking crisis.
Small credit organizations, without access to cheap resources, such as state banks, were forced to attract public funds at high interest rates.
In response, state banks came to the path of war and began to reduce credit rates, - continues the economist.
Small credit institutions cannot lend at the same interest rate, otherwise they will have a negative interest margin.
If the state banks do not abandon dumping, Russia faces a full-fledged banking crisis, believes Vasily Solodkov.
The deprivation of licenses of a number of banks in recent weeks, the economist considers a harbinger of mass collapse.
"The state banks themselves will not cope with this situation: the deposit insurance system was not originally designed for a systemic crisis," the head of the institute warns.
But consumption growth will slow down without a crisis of non-payments, the investment bank believes, due to the refusal to index the salaries of civil servants and the military, laid down in the current version of the draft budget.
Partially, the impact on consumption will be mitigated by the freezing of natural monopoly tariffs (and, as a consequence, a decrease in inflation).
But only partially: if investments do not grow (and there are no prerequisites for this yet - see the reference), consumption growth will still slow down, Goldman Sachs is sure.
Vladimir Pantyushin of Barclays Capital does not yet see the prerequisites for the implementation of pessimistic scenarios.
“The main risk is still falling oil prices,” he says.
According to him, the economy of Russia will begin to decline at the cost of oil below $ 90 / barrel.
Goldman Sachs also noted that the Central Bank is not yet able to reduce interest rates in the economy.
There is a paradoxical picture: inflation has decreased, and banks have begun to raise rates.
This may mean that they did not believe the Central Bank, which announced the transition to inflation targeting, "- said Clemens Grafe.
The interest rate policy of the Central Bank does not affect market rates, it only affects interbank lending rates.
“For the Central Bank, this is a collapse of all hopes,” said Clement Graff.
The money received at the Central Bank auctions is used by banks not to lend to the economy, but to manage their liquidity.
As soon as the rate decreases, the exchange rate changes immediately, this means that the funds are trying to go to speculation against the ruble.
“Sooner or later, the Central Bank will understand that this strategy does not work,” said Mr. Grafe and recalled that the state plans to release the ruble into “free circulation” by the end of 2015.
But you will either have to do it sooner, or raise the key rate of the Central Bank (5.5%), he believes.
According to him, the ruble is now artificially inflated by 10%.
There is only one way to lose weight, the expert concludes.
But if the Central Bank plunges into the financiers even a shadow of doubt that the elimination of the currency corridor is not part of the policy to weaken the ruble, it can bring down the ruble much stronger.
