Snowden is ready to “cooperate” with Germany on the issue of U.S. intelligence
Edward Snowden, the U.S. intelligence whistleblower, said he was ready to travel to Berlin to testify to the German parliament if the U.S. National Security Agency and its director, Keith Alexander, could not answer questions about their activities.
German lawmaker Hans-Christian Str<0xC3><0xB6>bele met with Mr Snowden in Russia on Thursday, where he was granted asylum to discuss his testimony in Germany.
In a letter from Mr. Snowden, which the MP presented to the media in Berlin on Friday, he said: “Although the result of my efforts has been clearly positive, my government continues to treat dissent as treason and seeks to criminalize political statements with criminal charges that do not provide any protection.”
But telling the truth is not a crime.
In the letter, Mr Snowden said he believed that the support of the international community could persuade the US government to drop criminal charges against him.
The charges brought by the U.S. Department of Justice include espionage and theft of state property.
Hans-Peter Friedrich, Germany’s interior minister, told Zeit Online: “If Mr. Snowden is willing to talk to German officials, we will find ways to make this possible.”
Relations between the U.S. and Germany have become strained after allegations that the NSA tapped Chancellor Angela Merkel’s phone.
Thomas Opperman, a lawmaker who heads the parliamentary group overseeing the intelligence service, said that if there is an opportunity to hear Mr. Snowden as a witness, “without putting him in danger and destroying relations with the United States completely,” it should be used.
Mr. Str<0xC3><0xB6>bele, a member of parliament from Germany’s Green Party, tweeted a picture of himself with Mr. Snowden.
During his visit to Russia, he was accompanied by two German journalists.
Mr. Stroebele said that, according to a lawyer for a former NSA contractor, Mr. Snowden would not have been able to return to Russia if he had left.
If Mr. Snowden were to testify in Germany, he would need assurances that he would be “safe there,” the lawmaker said.
Mr Snowden said in his letter that he faced a “hard and steady” harassment campaign that forced him to leave his home.
However, he said he was encouraged by the world’s reaction to “his political statements.”
Citizens around the world, as well as high-ranking officials — including in the United States — have found exposing an unchecked system of pervasive surveillance beneficial to society.
The letter contains a proposal to cooperate with the German authorities “when the difficulties of this humanitarian situation are resolved”.
Frontier Airlines will charge a fee for hand luggage
Frontier Airlines plans to charge passengers up to $100 for carrying hand luggage on board their flight.
Frontier Airlines plans to start charging up to $100 for hand luggage and $2 for coffee or soda, although its announcement on Wednesday said passengers would be able to keep the entire can.
The new hand luggage fee applies to bags in the upper luggage compartments, so small bags placed under the seat will remain free.
Frontier said it would charge $25 if the fee is paid in advance, and $100 if travelers will only pay once they are at the gate.
Frontier spokeswoman Kate O’Malley said the $100 fee should force passengers to take care of payment in advance.
“We don’t want to charge for it,” she said.
Airlines began charging for the first and second handbags in 2008.
Passengers trying to avoid these charges are stuffed as much as they can into hand luggage placed in the upper luggage compartments, which is why there is often not enough space in these compartments.
Charges are one way to get passengers to carry less on board.
O'Malley said that this new fee isn't really about making money.
The fact is that the most loyal Frontier customers say that finding a place in the upper luggage compartments is becoming increasingly difficult.
Passengers who buy tickets on the airline’s website will not have to pay.
This means that one passenger in the queue at the exit of the Frontier flight can get the opportunity to carry a bag for free, while the next passenger in the queue can pay $100 for the same bag.
O’Malley said the change of procedures on the website and at Frontier check-in counters is designed to ensure that passengers will be aware of the pickup before they get to the boarding gate.
The new Frontier hand luggage charge will not start until the summer, although the date has not yet been set.
Passengers often complain about baggage and other charges, but airlines love them.
They argue that baggage handling costs money, and passengers who need this service have to pay for it.
Many on Wall Street see the addition of baggage fees as a sign that airlines are charging enough money to cover the cost of air travel after years of losses.
However, most of them did not relate to the fees for hand luggage.
Spirit Airlines Inc. introduced the first hand luggage charge three years ago, and another Allegiant Air discounter later followed suit.
The only other airline with such a fee is Hungarian Wizz Air, said airline consultant Jay Sorensen, who closely monitors the surcharges.
According to his estimate in a December 2011 report, the fee for hand luggage brings Spirit $50 million a year.
Sorensen, a former Midwest Airlines top manager, recently flew on a Spirit flight, and was curious about what he would find at the boarding gate when passengers faced an unusual Spirit charge for hand luggage.
“The landing process was the smoothest I’ve seen in my airline career,” he said.
I expected to see teeth grinding and a skirmish at the landing gate.
The plane was full, he said, “and the landing was swift.”
Frontier also follows Spirit on a $2 fee for coffee, tea, soda or juice.
Frontier said that passengers who receive soda or juice can keep the entire can and that the coffee will be served free of charge.
She will continue to give away water free of charge.
US Airways briefly tried to charge for the drinks in 2008, but declined seven months later after passengers began complaining and no other major airline followed suit.
Frontier’s initiative to charge for hand luggage when passengers don’t buy tickets directly from the airline is its latest move to attract customers to its website.
Airlines pay online ticket sellers, such as Orbitz, $10 to $25 for each ticket sold.
This gave all airlines an incentive to encourage passengers to buy tickets directly from them, rather than contacting an online travel agency.
However, Frontier has gone further in this area.
In September, it began giving half the bonus miles of a frequent flyer to customers who bought tickets through an online travel agency.
On Wednesday, it cut the premium number of miles to 25 percent of the trip’s miles.
For example, a 1,000-mile trip with Frontier, purchased from an online travel agency, would allow you to get 250 miles.
In addition, passengers can choose a seat in advance only if they buy tickets directly on the Frontier website.
Frontier has a loyal customer base in her hometown of Denver, but its business is shrinking and becoming unprofitable.
Revenue fell 9 percent and flight capabilities fell nearly 13 percent in the first quarter, according to financial results released on Wednesday by parent company Republic Airways Holdings Inc.
The Republic is trying to fix Frontier's finances as part of the airline's sale.
The NSA blames “internal error” and not hackers in the termination of the site
The National Security Agency, shrouded in secrecy, said on Friday evening that the shutdown of their website for several hours caused a technical glitch, not hackers, as alleged on the network.
“NSA.gov was unavailable for several hours tonight due to an internal error that occurred during a scheduled update,” the agency said in an official email.
The problem will be solved tonight.
Claims that the outage was caused by a distributed denial-of-service (DDoS) attack are incorrect.
Earlier this evening, online server monitoring systems registered that the NSA website had been down for at least six hours and the site was still inaccessible to some users.
Earlier, a representative of the NSA told ABC News that the internal secret network of the agency “not at all” was hacked.
No classified information is in danger, the spokesman said.
At least one online group of activist hackers said it was responsible for disabling the NSA website through a DDoS attack.
DDoS attacks are designed to overwhelm the target site with traffic until the servers are overloaded and the site fails.
Hackers’ tactics are relatively simple, and attacks are not designed to penetrate the target system’s internal network.
The previously super-secret NSA, once nicknamed “No Such Agency,” has been in the spotlight in recent months after a string of revelations about its extensive surveillance programs abroad and domestically — all a reaction to classified NSA files stolen from the agency and published by a disillusioned former NSA employee.
The growing controversy surrounding the agency has sparked speculation that today’s incident was the result of targeted hacking.
Bombardier profit declines with falling deliveries and number of aircraft orders
Bombardier Corporation, a Canadian aircraft and train manufacturer, reported a 15 percent reduction in net profit on Thursday due to a decrease in orders and deliveries of aircraft in the third quarter and contract problems in its rail division.
Montreal-based Bombardier also did not release any flight test data for its newest CSeries aircraft, nor did it provide new information on whether ambitious plans to commercialize the aircraft by next September would be implemented.
After the first flight of the prototype aircraft, which took place about a month and a half ago, it flew only three more times, which raises questions about whether the stage of testing is on schedule.
The results did not meet forecasts and led to a fall in shares of more than 8 percent on the Toronto Stock Exchange.
Cameron Doerken, an analyst at National Bank Financial, downgraded his valuation on Thursday from “above-average” to “average” due to a belief that stock growth is limited in the coming quarter or two.
“While the decline in aircraft shipments was generally predictable, we are certainly disappointed with the revenue performance of the transportation department,” Doerxen said in a stock market review.
We believe Bombardier will receive new orders for CSeries as the flight test program continues.
However, if no new orders are announced in the coming months, we expect the market to become more skeptical of the program.
Bombardier hopes that the CSeries family of aircraft will allow it to win a place in the lower price segment of the market, which is now dominated by Boeing and Airbus.
The first prototype of the aircraft was presented in March and flew for the first time in September after several months of delay.
However, firm orders for the CSeries so far are not too many – 177, as potential buyers are waiting for the results of flight tests to verify the company’s claims about the fuel efficiency and potential economy of the new liner.
In total, there are now 403 orders and agreements with 15 customers and operators.
CEO Pierre Baudoin was confident that Bombardier would reach its target of 300 firm orders by the time the first aircraft was put into commercial service.
On Thursday, executives also assured analysts and the media that the program is moving forward as planned.
"The test model of the aircraft did not stay on the ground longer than expected," Baudouin said during a conference call, adding that ground tests and software updates were planned for the aircraft's downtime.
All manufacturers plan tests differently.
We decided to make the first flight and take a break for updates, so we did.
This will be the case throughout the flight test program.
The second of five test samples is due to fly in the coming weeks and all the others will soon follow, the company said.
Still, analysts are skeptical about the claim that the first customer will be able to start operating the CSeries aircraft 12 months after its first flight.
Bombardier said it was assessing the timing of the commissioning and would provide new information in the next few months.
“This slow pace of flight testing – while apparently consistent with Bombardier’s internal schedule – reinforces our view that commissioning will be pushed back to the first quarter of 2015,” Doerxen said.
In the third quarter ending Sept. 30, Bombardier’s net income fell to $147 million, or 8 cents per share, from $172 million, or 9 cents per share, last year.
Adjusted earnings per share remained unchanged at 9 cents.
Gross income decreased slightly - from $ 4.2 to $ 4.1 billion.
Analysts had expected earnings of 10 cents per share and gross income of $ 4.56 billion, according to Thomson Reuters I/B/E/S.
The world’s fourth-largest aircraft manufacturer said it delivered 45 aircraft per quarter, down from 57 the previous year.
The total number of orders fell from 83 to 26 aircraft.
The aerospace division’s order book totaled $32.9 billion as of September 30, unchanged from December 31.
"In the aerospace field, the results were in line with our goals, but the small number of incoming orders and the overall market conditions have become an unpleasant factor," Baudouin said.
Gross revenue in the aerospace sector fell by 13 percent to $2 billion.
Bombardier, the world’s largest train maker, said gross revenue in the sector rose nearly 11 percent to $2.1 billion.
The portfolio of orders in the transport division amounted to $32.6 billion as of September 30, which is slightly higher than the figure of December 31.
The revenues of the transport unit were negatively affected by problems with the execution of several large contracts.
The management said that a new development plan will be presented in the fourth quarter.
Shares of Bombardier, which also announced that Google chief financial officer Patrick Peachett will join the board of directors, fell 8.5 percent to C$4.83 at mid-Thursday's auction.
Brazil’s Embraer SA, the world’s third-largest commercial aircraft manufacturer and Bombardier’s closest competitor, said on Thursday it had cut its quarterly revenue by 10 percent.
Sony expects a lower annual profit
Japanese electronics manufacturer Sony Corporation, having completed the last quarter with a net loss of 19.3 billion yen, or $197 million, reduced its forecast for profit for the current fiscal year.
Sony’s performance between July and September 2013 was more disappointing than expected due to the drop in demand for Japanese-made TVs, camcorders and personal computers.
Sony’s television business, which brought the company its first operating profit of 5.2 billion yen in three years in the second quarter, fell again to 9.3 billion yen in the reporting period.
