The gene of speech was a stimulant of synapse formation
Scientists from Johns Hopkins University and Mount Sinai School of Medicine have discovered a protein through which the “voice gene” Foxp2 performs its function by stimulating the formation of new connections between neurons.
The study is published in Science, on the website of the journal you can read its summary.
The Foxp2 gene is the first known gene whose function is directly related to speech.
His role was established in 2001 thanks to the discovery of a family of several people who could not pronounce words correctly and sometimes did not even understand each other.
The researchers found that the Foxp2 gene was disrupted in the family members, but how it performs its function remains unknown.
In a new study, biologists have shown that at least part of its functions Foxp2 performs as a stimulant of the formation of new synapses in the brain area associated with the formation of speech.
It does this thanks to another gene, SRPX2.
The latter was discovered as a result of the search for factors that stimulate the formation of synapses.
SRPX2 turned out to be one of the 10 similar genes found by the authors, with Foxp2 showing only its activity.
The fact that SRPX2 really affects vocalization, scientists confirmed in an experiment on mice.
When the animals’ gene activity was artificially reduced, they screamed less when separated from their mother.
If the activity of the gene was restored, the frequency of sounds emitted was also restored.
Previously, mice were also shown to be associated with the vocalization of Foxp2 itself.
The animals injected with a human copy of the gene ate more actively and at a lower frequency than normal mice.
So far, however, scientists do not know whether Foxp2 and its SRPX2 are related to purely “mechanical” sound-forming properties or to more subtle processes.
