Concerns about security in Mozambique are growing due to the conflict of influential people
Under a top-down statue of Mozambique’s founding president, Zamora Machel, thousands of people gathered in the centre of Maputo to chant slogans about peace at one of the rare demonstrations here.
“We want peace back; we want stability,” said Vanessa de Sousa, chief executive of the investment firm.
Fearing for her country’s future, she changed her business suit to a T-shirt emblazoned with “We demand security” in Portuguese and joined the crowd at Independence Square on Thursday.
For two weeks, there were almost daily reports of clashes between government troops and Renamo, one of the most violent clashes since the armistice was signed more than 20 years ago.
Renamo was once a well-known insurgent movement that was supported first by the white authorities of Rhodesia and then by the apartheid-era government of South Africa as part of efforts to destabilize the country’s independent government.
After the 1992 armistice, it became an opposition party.
Analysts believe that the country is unlikely to slide back into full-scale conflict, but recent events have made foreign investors and local residents nervous.
The stakes are high for a fast-growing economy, as the discovery of huge offshore gas reserves and coal fields in the northwest could attract more than $50 billion in investment over the next few years from companies such as Rio Tinto, Vale from Brazil, Eni from Italy and Anadarko from the United States.
The ruling Frelimo party, a leading political force since 1975, and the Renamo party accuse each other of creating tensions.
Renamo's party claims that the government was the instigator of the latest clashes, attacking its members in Sofala province, the traditional Renamo stronghold, on October 17.
Attacks on former rebels then escalated as government forces attacked Renamo bases and tried to kill Afonso Dhlakama, the group’s leader, Fernando Mazanga, a spokesman for Renamo, told the Financial Times.
The government blames Renamo for initiating clashes, accusing the party of attacking soldiers.
President Armandu Gebuza has sought to allay fears of instability.
Gebuza told AFP, the French news agency, on Wednesday that Mr Dhlakama felt like a “loser” who wanted to use “all that is left of his strength to try to prove that he can impose his own decisions on the government.”
Both Frelimo and Renamo insist that they want to avoid war.
However, concerns grew after reports that Mazanga had announced Renamo's rejection of the 1992 peace agreement.
He told the Financial Times that he was referring to Frelimo’s non-compliance with the agreement.
“Our goal is to get back to negotiations, but in all seriousness,” Mazanga said.
Previous talks between the parties have done little to ease tensions, which have been exacerbated by a series of clashes this year.
“These are two influential people (Gebuza and Dhlakama) who collided with their foreheads,” said Joseph Hanlon, a lecturer at Open University and an expert on Mozambique.
None of them are good negotiators and none of them are willing to make the necessary concessions.
Renamo's party, which is trying to push through electoral reforms, has already said it will boycott municipal elections scheduled for November.
Presidential and parliamentary elections are scheduled for next year.
Some commentators interpreted this pressure as an attempt by the weakened movement to obtain concessions and financial bonuses from the government.
The share of votes for Renamo has been declining since 1992, while a new party, the Democratic Movement of Mozambique (MDM), which was founded by a former member of Renamo, is expected to improve its performance in this election.
Mr. Mazanga said that Mr. Gebuza, who was due to step down next year when his second term ended, wanted to destroy democracy in the country.
“He doesn’t want a multi-party democracy, he doesn’t want transparent elections, he doesn’t want peace because he doesn’t want to leave the presidency,” Mazanga said.
It is unclear what Renamo's capabilities are, but it has already carried out devastating and rapid attacks on police stations and cars on a key highway leading from north to south.
Most of the skirmishes took place in the province of Sofala, which is a few hundred kilometers north of Maputo, but includes Beira, a port that mining companies including Rio Tinto and Vale use to export coal.
In June, Rio suspended the use of railway tracks for about a week after Renamo threatened to attack the railway.
Mazanga was evasive when asked if Renamo would repeat the threat.
Renamo’s party wanted to “warn the international community that things are not going very well in Mozambique,” Mazanga said.
Instability has fueled discontent with the government, and many people are also concerned about corruption, slow development and the recent increase in kidnappings, says Fernando Lima, head of independent media company Mediacoop.
“People think that the responsibility for the future of the country lies with the government and the president, who must find a solution to these problems,” he says.
Omar Sultan, a participant in the demonstration, said people just want stability.
“Nobody cares about Renamo or Frelimo, they just want a renewal of the world, they want free access to the roads,” he said.
