Obama campaign considered Biden’s exception in favor of Hillary Clinton
According to The New York Times, the closest advisers of President Barack Obama secretly considered the possibility of replacing Vice President Joe Biden with Hillary Clinton on the 2012 electoral list.
This discovery is the brightest sensation of all the expected book by Mark Halperin and John Heilemann about the 2012 campaign “The stakes are doubled: the game has changed in 2012”.
The Times obtained a copy of the forthcoming book and reported on Thursday evening that the president’s closest aides conducted “large-scale focus group research and opinion polls at the end of 2011” to assess whether Biden’s exclusion could help raise fading hopes for Obama’s re-election.
According to The Times political columnist Jonathan Martin, the book provides a detailed description of an attempt by senior campaign officials and the White House, namely former White House chief of staff Bill Daley, to assess the impact of the election on the appointment of former Secretary of State Clinton as vice president.
The possible replacement was a secret, carefully guarded at the Chicago campaign headquarters and in the Oval Office.
Only six of the president’s closest advisers — including Daley, former Obama campaign chairman Jim Messina, and former senior White House advisers David Axelrod and David Pluff — knew the replacement was under consideration.
The book Double Bets claims that Daly was the initiator of the attempt to replace Biden, despite their "close personal relationship", but eventually abandoned this step when their data showed that adding Clinton to the electoral list would not "significantly improve Obama's chances".
In an interview with Martin Daly confirmed that the administration was indeed considering the possibility of replacing Biden Clinton.
“I’ve been very vocal about a lot of things, and that was one of them,” Daley told the paper.
You have to remember that the president was in terrible shape at the time, so we thought, ‘Oh my God, what are we going to do?’
Although Daley described the study as a “necessary test,” Martin told CNN’s Anderson Cooper that the campaign had invested heavily in examining whether the move would yield a dividend on the vote.
“Election headquarters don’t spend that kind of money on polls and focus groups unless they’re taking something seriously,” Martin said on the AK 360 program.
It is unclear, however, whether Obama knew that his team was exploring the possibility of a replacement.
Martin told CNN that he asked Daley if his then-boss knew of a possible shuffle.
Although Daley said he didn’t think the president “was aware” of a possible replacement, the former administration chief admitted that, “maybe,” Obama knew.
Martin added that Double Bets does not give a clear answer to the question of whether the results of political probing have reached the Obama table.
Cooper asked Martin if he thought Obama was serious about exploring the possibility of removing Biden from the electoral roll.
“Maybe,” said Martin.
