Halloween 2013 in numbers
When I was a kid, Halloween was magical.
My sister and I were allowed to eat sweets, it was too late not to go to bed and arrange a masquerade for our district.
I'm more of a scumbag now.
I haven’t been asked to hand out candy in my apartment in the last two years, and I probably won’t this year either.
However, statistics show that I am a white crow when it comes to Halloween.
According to the National Retail Federation, most Americans — 158 million — will celebrate Halloween this year and spend a total of $6.9 billion on candy, costumes and jewelry.
The only thing I look forward to every Halloween is trends.
The National Retail Federation predicts that the costumes will cost $1.2 billion out of the $6.9 billion spent.
This year at the peak of fashion sexual inanimate objects.
Women no longer need to be sex workers; they can also be sex food, such as pizza, hamburgers, or carrots.
As for the men, I think we’ll see a lot of zombies thanks to The Walking Dead, and I’m sure Daft Punk-style cosmonauts will hit our Instagram feeds this year.
According to Google, the costumes most often searched for are zombies, Batman, pirates and witches.
There is nothing wrong with the traditional approach.
We dressed our dogs last year and, to my surprise, we weren’t the only ones.
Moreover, according to the National Retail Federation, Americans will spend $330 million this year on pet costumes.
That means a lot of funny dogs.
When it comes to sweets, we don’t mince words.
Americans will spend $1.9 billion on them this year, according to Nielsen.
That’s about 600 million pounds of Hershey chocolates, lollipops, Milk Duds candy, Twizzlers chewing candy, and Clark Bar bars.
According to the U.S. Department of Commerce, this is great news for the 41 million candy-demanding children who have prepared to conquer our neighborhoods.
Moreover, we will buy and – let’s not fool ourselves – eat 90 million pounds of chocolate during Halloween.
The only thing we don’t want to eat is sweets in the form of corn kernels; and yet, according to the National Confectionery Association, nearly 35 million pounds of them are sold on Halloween.
That’s about 9 billion individual corn kernels.
This is a mystery that I have yet to solve.
Nothing expresses the essence of Halloween so much as at home with ghosts.
They have amazing names, such as “The Horror Behind the Walls” (which, by the way, is in a real prison), “Howl and Scream” and “House of Shock”.
Moreover, according to the America Haunts Society, there are 1,200 officially recognized haunted houses in America, generating about $500 million in revenue, as well as those amazing photos where you almost described yourself, which your friend posted on Facebook and you can’t remove, and then the guy you like sees this photo and leaves a comment like “cool facial expression.”
Finally, let’s talk about pumpkins.
Charlie Brown introduced us to the Big Pumpkin when we were kids, and carving out Jack’s lamp is like decorating a Christmas tree, something we’ve been doing since childhood.
Luckily for us, baby fashion in pumpkins only started last year thanks to Pinterest, so most of us grew up cutting out those pumpkins rather than sitting in them.
According to the U.S. Census Bureau, this year Americans will spend about $106 million on pumpkins.
Jack’s lamp, slowly drying out on your porch, probably came from the state of Illinois, which has grown 542 million pounds of pumpkin this year.
If you want more challenging tasks, visit Tim and Susan Mathisdon in Napa, California, and try cutting out some of their 2032-pound pumpkins.
