George Kerevan: Breaking with Europe gives Scots a choice
Another day, another scarecrow about independence.
This time we are being warned that an independent Scotland will have to join a pan-European free movement zone as a condition of EU membership.
There are a number of stories about passport control in Berwick and the border with barbed wire along the Adrianople Wall.
True, the newspaper Strathclyde pointed to the possible economic benefits of freer movement across the rest of Europe, although – predictably – it did not appear in the headlines.
Nor did anyone point out that EU member states spend a lot of time turning their formal rules around as they see fit.
As Scotland is not now part of the Schengen area, continued non-compliance would be a cheap concession for Brussels in exchange for what it really wanted from the Scots.
So this is not a noteworthy story.
And so old that it became a fossil: the first time I heard the “duck” that “independence means passport control” was at least 40 years ago.
And yet there is an interesting moment lost in the retelling of an old fairy tale.
Why should an independent Scotland follow the orders of Europe?
Why change the yoke of London to the yoke of Brussels, especially now?
Here is the real European news: the great post-war plan to unite Europe has finally stalled.
With the euro crisis, the Europe project is officially dead.
Across the European Union, parties opposing the EU or calling for the abolition of the euro as the single currency are gaining momentum.
Even in Germany, the Eurosceptic Alternative for Germany party – founded only this year – emerged out of nowhere and won almost five million votes in the September federal elections, thus essentially ousting the Free Democrats (an analogue of our Liberal Democrats) from the Bundestag.
There has always been internal opposition to the plan to create a federal Europe.
Nevertheless, the current economic crisis has been a watershed moment.
The austerity measures imposed by Berlin and the European Central Bank, and the shackles imposed on national economies through the preservation of the single currency, have led many people to think that the Europe project has gone too far.
The euro crisis has little to do with national governments running excessive budget deficits – this was only true for Greece.
In fact, the euro system has locked its members in exchange rates that are beneficial to German exporters – something that German politicians want to preserve.
Without the possibility of devaluation of the national currency, southern Europe finds itself at a pre-disadvantage in terms of production capacity compared to Germany.
The only way to save money is to cut salaries and public spending, which is actively supported by Berlin.
Behind the current budget and currency problems is the deeper problem of Europe’s productive capacity.
As a result of the set of measures on “green” energy introduced by Brussels, a code that means subsidizing French and German energy companies at the expense of consumers, European industry pays twice as much for electricity and four times more for gas than in the United States.
These are paralyzingly unfavourable price conditions, as we have seen in Grangemouth.
No global wage freeze will stop the crushing victory of cheap U.S. shale gas over Europe’s petrochemical industry.
As a result, a rebellion is brewing, especially in France, once the EU’s most ardent supporter.
After the war, the French political elite saw the EU as a way to control Germany and put Paris on par with Washington.
But Berlin no longer needs Paris as a means of gaining political legitimacy, and has already imposed its own economic policies on Europe, leaving France’s shattered economy in dire straits.
The result is Marine Le Pen’s right-wing, anti-EU National Front party has just won a crucial re-election, dropping the ruling Socialist Party to third place.
The Front is now the most popular party in France with 24 per cent of the vote – a timely warning to British Labour that it is impossible to assume that a split among the right will automatically affect the left.
What is Le Pen doing with her newfound popularity among the French white working class?
She wants to use the EU elections next year to create a bloc in the European Parliament against the EU and against the single currency.
If – and this is very likely – anti-EU parties gain support in these elections, such a bloc will be able to take a dominant position in the European Parliament for the first time.
Here is my opinion: soon the growing sentiment against the EU and against the single currency in Europe will merge to destroy the euro.
The EU will not disappear, but it will again become something of a vague “Europe of (sovereign) nations” that General de Gaulle liked.
Germany and several of its dependent economies can keep the euro, but France and southern Europe will restore their own currencies.
I assume that the UK is distancing itself from this project, hoping to get closer to the US.
Nevertheless, Washington’s growing interest in the Pacific indicates the likelihood that the UK will remain unattended in the cold of the Atlantic.
Where does that leave Scotland?
We can choose to become a region (essentially) of Little England.
Or we can defend our own economic interests, which means, among other things, sending Berlin and Brussels to hell.
I suspect that Scotland will be able to succeed under a freer European arrangement provided we keep our currency.
Cooperation with other like-minded countries will be easier in a non-federal Europe of nations.
Otherwise, we should consider repeating Norway ' s experience and preserving our economic independence.
The Scottish National Party government in Scotland is, oddly enough, the most successful anti-austerity political movement in Europe, winning an overwhelming majority of votes in 2011 thanks to objections to spending cuts proposed (and implemented) by Labour’s Chancellor of the Exchequer, Alistair Darling, and the ensuing Tory-Liberal Democrat coalition.
It would now be absurd for Scotland to vote for independence just to take austerity measures imposed by Berlin and Brussels.
Early puberty: Aging earlier
African-American and Latino girls tend to reach puberty earlier than their white peers, research shows.
Physical changes do not mean that puberty is near
There is no evidence that hormones or other chemicals are to blame.
Experts believe that the obesity epidemic may be one of the triggers of early puberty
The tendency to early puberty is not so pronounced in boys
Former CNN correspondent Pat Etheridge is a journalist specializing in children's health and family issues.
Should a mother be afraid if her daughter begins to form the germs of the breast and grow pubic hair at 7 or 8 years old?
At the American Academy of Pediatrics’ annual conference this week in Orlando, Florida, pediatric endocrinologist Dr. Paul Kaplovitz explained that these early physical changes are quite common among American girls and represent a new norm.
“I spend a lot of time calming my parents down — usually that doesn’t mean a rapid onset of full sexual maturity,” Kaplovitz said.
Obvious signs of development, such as growing breasts, pubic and armpit hair, and body odor, appear earlier in girls.
But there has only been a slight shift in menarche age (first menstruation) over the past four decades.
In the United States, the average age is 12.5 years, down from 12.75 in 1970.
“Once the breasts start to develop, it’s at least two to three years before menarche,” said Kaplovitz, who is also the author of “Early Sexual Maturity in Girls: How to Cope with This Common Problem.”
Time is the most accurate test of how puberty will progress.
There is a debate about what constitutes the actual onset of puberty, but it is considered "premature" when breast enlargement is accompanied by a sharp increase in growth to 8 years.
In most cases, the process will slow down or stop – something the pediatrician can monitor closely.
Faster progression can serve as a basis for endocrinologist tests to rule out serious problems such as tumors or cysts.
There are procedures to delay early menstruation and prevent another consequence: premature bone aging, which can eventually lead to stunted growth and low growth in adulthood.
Recommendations for drug or hormonal therapy are based on the child's age, level of development, growth rate, and emotional maturity.
The psychosocial aspects are also important.
Kaplowitz is cautious about medication, but admits that “repression of puberty can alleviate girls’ behavioral problems and feelings that they are different from their peers.”
Another big problem is clear: parents just don’t want their very young daughters to have menstruation.
“They’re worried about the risk of pregnancy or even how they’ll handle hygiene issues,” Kaplovitz said.
“It was a shock,” recalls one woman, whose daughter began menstruating at the age of 10.
Although there were signs and we were talking about menstruation, she wasn’t emotionally ready.
She came home from school scared and upset that she was the first among her friends.
There are many theories about the causes of early puberty.
However, there is no consistent evidence that hormones in milk or other foods, chemicals in the environment, or sexual messages in the media are to blame.
In boys, as in girls, puberty comes earlier.
Kaplovitz argues that the premise that has the greatest weight is the obesity epidemic.
In 2001, he helped to conduct a study of girls from 6 to 9 years old, which links the amount of fat in the body with puberty.
Other evidence supports this conclusion, but there are many other contributing factors.
In this country, African-American and Latino girls tend to reach puberty earlier than their white peers.
There are various explanations.
Around the world, early puberty appears to be affected by everything from economic conditions and climate to genes.
Another mystery: although boys have facial and pubic hair at a younger age, the tendency to full early puberty is not as pronounced as in girls.
Other doctors attending the AAP conference confirmed the complexity of the topic.
The appearance of pimples and pubic hair occurs even in infants and children of nursery age.
“We need to be careful about how we determine the true onset of puberty,” said Dr. Lawrence Silverman, a pediatric endocrinologist at Gorieb Children’s Hospital in Morristown, New Jersey.
Parents should not be ashamed to receive instructions from the pediatrician on how to talk to their child.
“This could mean an earlier than expected conversation,” Kaplovitz explained.
If you stay calm, your child will usually respond well.
Girls who bloom early need confirmation that even when it happens earlier than expected, this process is a normal part of life.
