Pawnshop owners in Singapore are doing well, while the middle class is struggling
In a pawnshop in Singapore’s Bendemir shopping mall, Janani Amirthalinga pawns a gold bracelet, a ring and earrings to pay for her daughter’s schooling.
“My husband and I just bought a house, so all my money is invested there,” says Ms. Amirthalinga.
Although she earns S$3,000 ($2,400) a month as an administrator and her husband also works, the family’s monthly income isn’t enough, she says.
Indeed, demand in various parts of Southeast Asia — where household debt is rising — is such that ValueMax, where it conducts its deal, this week became the third pawnshop to be listed on the Singapore Stock Exchange.
A mortgage on jewelry is not just a quick way to get money (S$1,300 in Ms. Amirthaling’s case), but almost as cheap as unsecured bank loans.
Pawnshops in Singapore typically charge an effective annual interest rate of 17% — just above the 15.4% offered by the United Overseas Bank branch, a local lender with a branch in the same mall.
However, pawnshops have the advantage that they do not require a credit check or proof of salary and can issue loans faster than banks.
Therefore, millions of people across the region are turning to pawnshops as families feel pressured by rising cost of living and the rapid rise in household debt and consumer debt.
After five years of steady growth following the global financial crisis and cheap credit fueled by free monetary policy in advanced economies, low- and middle-income families are turning to pawnshops to compensate for declining incomes as their economies slow.
This week, Standard & Poor’s, a rating agency, pointed to an increase in the family’s leverage, mainly due to rising mortgages, as a risk factor for the creditworthiness of Asian banks.
It said Malaysia, Thailand and Singapore had the highest ratio of household debt to gross domestic product in Asia.
Malaysia topped the list with 80% of GDP compared to 60% in 2008.
Economists are also concerned about the high level of consumer debt in Thailand, which this week barely came out of a technical recession.
On Thursday, data showed continued declines in exports and weakening consumer demand.
“The bottom line is that as prices rise, people in the middle and bottom of the [income scale] will look for ways to top up their income where they can,” says Song Seng-wun, an economist at CIMB, a Malaysian bank.
The record high gold prices over the past two years have intensified the haste with which people pawn their personal belongings as they take advantage of the opportunity to get paid for their family jewelry.
In Singapore, about 70% of the things laid in the 200 pawnshops of the city-state are gold products.
People say, “The price of gold looks good, let’s put on Grandma’s gold chain and get it back next month.”
In Thailand, the largest pawnshop operator EasyMoney has seen an increase in the number of customers using its branches in recent months, up to 20%.
The growth in the pawnshop business is such that ValueMax, the operator of the Bendemire branch and 15 others in Singapore, plans to expand not only in neighboring Malaysia, where it has four stores, but also outside Asia too, says Yeah Li Ching, CEO of ValueMax.
The company will fund the expansion, using 60 percent of the S$66 million raised this week as a result of the stock offering on the Singapore Stock Exchange.
While some lenders have caused fire criticism due to high interest rates, Ms. Yeah says that the pawnshop not only offers cheaper tariffs than other lenders, it also does not increase the debt directly.
“Clients mortgage items they already own, and monetizing personal assets doesn’t increase household debt,” she says.
The institution is gaining increasing public recognition as a means to obtain short-term, secured funding.
And at the same time, pawnshops are used not only by those categories of people who are in a difficult financial situation.
Wealthy people in Singapore also use ValueMax branches, pawning gold bars or Rolex watches, which can give up to 60 percent of their purchase value in cash.
We see clients from all walks of life.
“These include wealthy individuals who need to borrow money for short-term commercial projects or investments, or small businesses who need to overcome temporary monetary difficulties,” says Ms. Yeah.
Sometimes they just need the money very quickly.
