FAU: “Air passengers can now use gadgets on airplanes (but not call from a mobile phone)”
Air passengers will be able to use their electronic devices throughout the flight to read, work, play games, watch movies and listen to music, but not talk on mobile phones, according to the long-awaited new guidelines published Thursday by the Federal Aviation Administration.
But passengers should not expect the changes to happen immediately.
How quickly such a change is implemented will vary depending on the airline, FAU administrator Michael Huerta said at a press conference.
Airlines will have to show the FAA how their aircraft comply with the new guidelines and that they are updating their flight crew training manuals and device stacking rules to comply with the new guidelines.
The FAA said it had already received plans from some airlines to expand the use of portable electronic devices in aircraft.
Delta and JetBlue were among the airlines that have already submitted plans.
“Depending on the state of the plan, we could approve an expansion in the use of electronic devices very soon,” the FAU said.
Passengers are now required to turn off their smartphones, tablets and other devices as soon as the plane door closes.
They should not restart them until the plane reaches a height of 10,000 feet and the captain gives a "good".
Passengers should turn off their devices again when the plane is descending for landing, and not turn them on until the plane is on the ground.
Under the new guidelines, airlines whose planes are adequately protected against electronic interference may allow passengers to use these devices during takeoff, landing and taxiing, the FAA said.
Most new airliners and other aircraft modified to allow passengers to use Wi-Fi at high altitudes are expected to meet these criteria.
Laura Glading, president of the Association of Professional Flight Attendants, welcomed the changes.
“Once the new policy is safely implemented (and we are going to work closely with the carrier to achieve this) it will be a win-win,” Glading said.
We are frankly tired of feeling “on duty at school” when it comes to this issue.
But internet connections for surfing, exchanging emails, texting or downloading data will still be banned at an altitude of less than 10,000 feet, the agency said.
Passengers will be asked to switch their smartphones, tablets and other devices to airplane mode.
Thus, there are still no "Words with friends" - an intelligent Internet game that actor Alec Baldwin played on his smartphone in 2011, when a sensational case occurred: the actor was removed from an American Airlines plane for refusing to turn off the device while the plane was at the gate for landing.
And heavier devices, such as laptops, will still need to be stowed in the luggage compartment, as they can injure someone if they fly around the cabin.
Calls from mobile phones in flight will also continue to be prohibited.
Regulatory powers over telephone calls belong to the Federal Communications Commission, not the FAA.
FAA may lift ban on some electronic devices during takeoff and landing
Last month, Mark Rosenker of the National Transportation Safety Board, a national transportation safety expert at CBS News, said cell phones were still considered a risk.
“Cell phones are really a problem, not only because they can potentially create interference for navigation devices, but we know through the FCC that they can create interference for cell towers when the plane is in the air,” Rosenker said.
The industry advisory committee set up by the FAA to look into the matter recommended last month that the government allow for greater use of personal electronic devices.
In recent years, there has been increasing pressure on the FAA to ease restrictions on their use.
Critics, such as Missouri Democratic Senator Claire McCaskill, argue that there are no compelling security reasons for the bans.
Compliance with the restrictions is also becoming increasingly difficult to enforce, as the use of devices has become ubiquitous.
Some studies show that up to a third of passengers forget or ignore instructions to turn off their devices.
The FAA began restricting the use of electronic devices by passengers in 1966 in response to reports of interference to navigation and communication equipment, when passengers began carrying FM radios, high-tech gadgets of the time.
New airliners are much more reliant on electrical systems than previous generations of aircraft, but they are also being developed and approved by the FAA as being resistant to electronic interference.
Airlines have been offering passengers Wi-Fi at cruising altitude for several years.
Aircraft modified for Wi-Fi systems are also more resistant to interference.
The vast majority of airliners are geared for wider use of electronic devices under the new guidelines, Huerta said.
Today’s electronic devices typically emit radio signals of much lower power than previous generations of devices.
E-book readers, for example, emit only minimal signals when browsing pages.
But signals become more powerful when devices load or send data.
Among those who sought to ease restrictions on the use of electronic devices by passengers was Amazon.com.
In 2011, representatives of the company downloaded an entire airliner with their Kindle e-book readers and flew on it to check for problems, but never found them.
Members of the FAU Advisory Committee expressed mixed feelings as to whether the use of the devices posed any risk.
Douglas Kidd, of the National Air Passenger Association, said he believes the interference from the devices is real, even if the risk is minimal.
Other committee members have said there are only individual pilots’ reports confirming that the devices can interfere with aviation systems, and most of these reports are very old.
However, the committee recommended that the FAA allow pilots to require passengers to turn off devices during instrument landings in conditions of limited visibility.
A group of representatives of the tourism industry welcomed these changes, calling them a sensible step towards the passengers, who are now using many technological devices.
“We are pleased that the FAA recognizes that passenger comfort is not incompatible with safety and security,” said Roger Dow, CEO of the U.S. Travel Association.
