Is the elite of Europe ready to do business with England?
The Business for Britain campaign was launched in April with a commitment to bring together business representatives and identify what changes Britain’s wealth and jobs creators want to see in its relationship with the EU.
To this end, we have commissioned the largest and most comprehensive survey of UK business leaders, asking them to express their thoughts on the UK, business and the EU.
YouGov surveyed more than 1,000 business leaders representing a wide range of businesses in the UK by size, sector and region.
The findings of the survey will come as a surprise to many.
We found that the vast majority of businesses are currently looking for export opportunities outside Europe, with a particular focus on countries that are modernizing and growing while EU countries are stagnant.
They want the government to prioritize new trade ties with countries such as China, India and Brazil, rather than wasting time on the long and difficult process of reforming the EU’s tangled institutions.
When asked about their views on specific policy issues, from antitrust regulation to product laws, most business leaders felt that control of these key areas of competence should be returned to Westminster.
There was general dissatisfaction with the single market, with business representatives saying that the costs of regulation from Brussels now outweigh the benefits of being in the European trade zone, even 40 percent of large enterprises, traditionally the most pro-European of all companies, agreed with this.
Last but not least, our survey of business leaders revealed that a clear majority wants the UK to pursue a treaty change and a relationship with the EU based on trade rather than politics.
This result, which has been observed among businesses of all sizes and the largest business groups, shows that businesses are pushing for a “significant change” that will bring powers back to the UK.
The stakes are high – achieving treaty changes and more favourable terms for the UK would provide a 16 per cent shift in the vote to remain in the EU.
The prime minister should have no doubt: this survey shows that British business supports his plan to revise the terms of Britain’s EU membership.
It also shows that businesses expect the revision to lead to a significant shift in the current balance of power back towards the UK.
Better conditions for British business are possible and increasingly necessary as the eurozone embarks on the path of closer economic and financial integration.
Priority should be given to jobs and economic growth in the UK and, as our survey results show, for business this means an increased focus on trade and fundamental changes in Brussels’ regulatory activities.
