Scientists have shed light on how the movements of the dog’s tail are related to its mood.
Earlier studies have shown that satisfied dogs wagging their tail to the right (from the dog’s point of view), while anxious dogs wagging their tail predominantly to the left.
But now scientists say other members of the canine family can spot and respond to these subtle differences in tail wagging.
Professor Giorgio Vallortigara, a neuroscientist at the University of Trento, says: “It is well known that in humans, the left and right sides of the brain are involved in different ways in the formation of stimuli that cause positive or negative emotions.”
Here we tried to look at this and other species.
He added that, just like humans, dogs’ right brain controls the left side of the body and vice versa, and the two hemispheres play different roles in emotions.
To learn more about how dogs respond to the diverse barking of other dogs’ tails, the researchers observed the animals as they watched movies about other dogs.
They measured the heart rate of the animals and analyzed their behavior.
We will probably soon understand why their tails sometimes point in one direction and sometimes in the other.
Professor Vallortigara said: “We showed the dogs videos of the dogs – either naturalistic versions or a silhouette to get rid of any other distorting factors, and we could manipulate the movement of the tail and direct the tail more to the left or right.”
When the animals saw that the otherwise unexpressed dog moved its tail to the right (in terms of the tail-wagging dog), they remained completely relaxed.
But when they noticed that the tail stooped predominantly to the left (again from the point of view of the tailed dog), their heartbeats increased and they looked anxious.
Professor Vallortigara said he did not think the dogs were intentionally communicating with each other through these movements.
In fact, he believes that dogs learned from their experience which movements they should worry about and which ones they shouldn’t.
He observes: “If there are multiple encounters with other dogs and often their tails in one direction are associated with more friendly behavior, and the right side gives less friendly behavior, then the dog reacts based on this experience.”
The researchers say these findings could give owners, veterinarians and trainers a deeper understanding of their animal’s emotions.
Dog behavior expert John Bradshaw, a visiting research fellow at the University of Bristol’s School of Veterinary Medicine, said this was not the first study to test whether left and right sides matter to dogs.
Last year, a group of scientists from Lincoln University found that dogs turn their heads to the left when looking at an aggressive dog, and to the right when looking at a happy dog.
And in another study at the University of Victoria in Canada, he reported: “Dogs were more likely to approach a robot dog when its tail was pointing to the left rather than the right, instead of becoming alarmed — the opposite of the Italian study.”
He said the differences could have been due to the fact that dogs in various studies did not fully perceive animals in movies or robot dogs as dogs.
It might be useful to study how dogs respond to real dogs, he explained.
“While there is sufficient evidence for different mammals that the two hemispheres of the brain are used for different purposes, many details have yet to be clarified, and dogs are no exception,” he said.
However, given the ease with which their behavior can be recorded, we will probably soon understand why their tails sometimes point in one direction and sometimes in the other.
