Pope Francis to name first cardinals in February
Pope Francis will raise the new cardinals of the Catholic Church for the first time in his term of office on February 22, as announced by the Vatican on Thursday.
Cardinals are the highest clergy in the Catholic Church after the pope, and it is they who elect the pope, so Francis will appoint his first group of people who will ultimately participate in the selection of his successor.
There are currently 201 cardinals.
However, after the cardinal reaches the age of 80, he can no longer participate in the election of the pope – this is the prerogative of a group of 120 “cardinal electors”.
In announcing the news, Vatican spokesman Father Federico Lombardi said a meeting of all current cardinals known as the Consistory would be held before the ceremony.
“Pope Francis has decided to announce in advance his decision to convene a consistory in February in order to facilitate the planning of other meetings involving cardinals from different parts of the world,” Lombardi said.
Jack Valero of Catholic Voices said the number of cardinal electors is likely to decline by February.
He said the pope usually calls as many cardinals as necessary to bring the number of electoral cardinals back to 120, as well as as as many cardinals over the age of 80 as he wishes.
The consistory next year will be of great importance because it will be the first since Francis was elected in March this year, according to Valero.
At the moment, there is a kind of bias in favor of Europe and especially in favor of Italy.
“It will be interesting to see if the new pope will appoint cardinals from other regions of the world to restore balance,” he said.
In South America, forty percent of Catholics live, but they are represented by a small number of cardinals.
They will also be the first elected cardinals since Francis formed the Council of Cardinals, a group of eight cardinals from around the world tasked with finding ways to reform the church.
In the past, the father decided everything on his own.
“Now Francis has chosen eight cardinals to help him,” Valero said.
He said it was “quite possible” that Francis would turn to the cardinals for advice.
But we haven’t been in this situation before – it’s the first time for us.
Valero said that the popes usually raised cardinal bishops from large parishes, but Francis “is full of surprises – so we don’t know who he will name.”
