Criticism of Obama's Voter Desperation
I voted for President Obama twice, sharing the hope of change.
He says Obama allowed Republican obstructionism to frustrate laudable efforts.
Obstructionism cannot serve as a justification for problems with the website of the Obama-reforming health care system, drone attacks
The Obama campaign memoirs of 2008 are a sad reminder of what could have been
Nathaniel P. Morris is a second-year medical student at Harvard University.
I'm reading a very sad book these days.
I thought that this book would inspire me during my somber second year of medical school and revive a sense of hope in me.
It’s called “Courage to Win,” and it’s a memoir of Barack Obama’s 2008 presidential campaign.
When I finish writing patient reports in the evening and go to bed, this book takes me back to a time when politics inspired millions of people and performances could be breathtaking.
The election victory was impressive, and news anchors paused to reflect on this historic moment.
My classmates were crying with joy, and my parents were guarding all the newspapers they could find.
A young team of strategists was to come to the White House, and the people were ready for change.
When Obama took office in 2008, his support rate was 82%.
Then I close the book.
Returning to the present is a rude awakening, like pulling out of a dream.
It’s hard to remember those days of optimism – they seem like a distant memory, a sad reminder of missed opportunities.
In the years since I dropped my first ballot, change has really happened.
It was something I couldn't even imagine.
I pay tribute to Obama for his great and varied accomplishments, from passing the Affordable Care Act to withdrawing our military from Iraq, repealing the “Don’t Ask, Don’t Tell” rule, and killing Osama bin Laden.
Moreover, I believe that party obstructionism has blocked too many attempts to move our country forward: immigration reform, the choice of public health, and the closure of the Guantanamo base among others.
But after countless times that I have sided with the Obama administration in defending it in front of colleagues and peers, I have run out of explanations that I can provide.
I have reached a point of political desperation.
Republican obstructionism cannot explain permission to wiretap foreign leaders or drone strikes on innocent children in other countries.
It cannot explain the National Security Agency’s collection of data on Americans’ private lives or the prosecution of whistleblowers exposing the government’s misconduct.
He cannot explain the murder of an American citizen, Anwar al-Awlaki, without trial or investigation, or the failure to comply with limits on government funding and spending during presidential campaigns.
He cannot justify the report’s findings, which say the White House’s efforts to silence the media are “the most aggressive ... since the Nixon administration.”
And lately, he can’t justify failing to develop a simple website for more than three years after signing the Affordable Care Act.
I don't know if I should have expected that.
Should I have known at the age of 18 that leadership could contradict the political campaigns that preceded it?
It is obvious that the work in the elected office is not a predictable program of action, because our public dialogue will be formed by the opposition political party and such random events as the massacre in Newtown.
Nevertheless, it is clear from all the examples I have listed above that they were largely the administration's own choice.
And that's what worries me the most.
I voted for Obama again in 2012, but not because I was enthusiastic about his candidacy.
Mitt Romney was an incomprehensible and crude alternative, it seemed that he was unable to make a decision on his own policies or views.
I believed that in his second term, Obama, freed from the pressure of future elections, would live up to the hopes we had heard about for so long.
However, when Obama’s approval rating fell below 45% this week, it became much more difficult to return to 2008 through this book.
It makes me yearn for the many promises that have flown by.
This week I read the part of the book that describes how Clinton dealt Obama a stunning defeat in the Pennsylvania primary.
At a meeting to analyze the reasons for the failure, he told his staff that they should get back on track and stay true to their goal.
“I want us to bring back our attraction,” he said.
We have to remember who we are.”
It's been five years, Mr. President, and I totally agree with you.
The views expressed in this commentary belong exclusively to Nathaniel Morris.
