Travel through mud, rivers and the jungle to provide free medical care
Dr. Georges Bwelle provides free medical care in the countryside of Cameroon
Bwelle and his team spend nearly every weekend taking in hundreds of patients.
There are not many doctors in this West African country – only one in 5,000 people.
Vote here or through your mobile device
Dr. Georges Bwelle is one of the 10 main characters of CNN in 2013.
You can vote for him or any of the other 10 main characters to make him the CNN Hero of the Year.
This man will receive $250,000 to continue his outstanding work.
For 21 years, Georges Bwelle saw his father come back to life and fall unconscious again, wandering through hospitals that were not properly equipped to help him.
Jamef Bwelle was injured in a car accident in 1981 near Yaoundé, the capital of Cameroon.
At first, he only had a broken arm, but the resulting infection spread to the brain and caused a hematoma that reminded him of himself for the rest of his life.
“There were no neurosurgeons in Cameroon,” said Georges Bwelle.
If we had the money, we would have taken it out of Cameroon.
Instead, Bwelle accompanied his father for years in overcrowded clinics and hospitals, receiving whatever treatment they could get.
“It’s not easy,” Bwelle said.
You can leave home at 5 a.m., run to the hospital to be the first, but you’re not the first.
There are a lot of patients.
Some may die because of what they have to wait for.
The situation hasn’t changed much since Bwelle’s father died in 2002.
According to the World Health Organization, Cameroon has only one doctor per 5,000 people.
For comparison, the ratio in the United States is one doctor per 413 people.
And even if Cameroonians could go to the doctor, many of them would be out of pocket.
Two out of five people in this country live below the poverty line, and almost three-quarters of healthcare spending in it is private.
“Their only problem is poverty,” Bwelle said.
“And because of poverty, they can’t enjoy their lives.”
Seeing the suffering of his father and so many of his compatriots, Bwelle was determined to do something about it.
Last year, Dr. Georges Bwelle and his team of volunteers conducted 700 free surgeries.
He became a doctor himself and works as a vascular surgeon at Yaoundé Central Hospital.
He also founded the non-profit organization ASCOVIME, which organizes trips to the countryside on weekends to provide free medical care.
Since 2008, he and his group of volunteers have assisted nearly 32,000 people.
Almost every Friday, he and up to 30 other people packed into vans, tied medical supplies to roofs and drove across rough terrain to visit villages in need of help.
They are not always lucky.
More than once they had to push cars across rivers and mud.
But when they arrive, they are greeted like real heroes: it is a holiday with songs and dances and the best rooms that the locals have to offer.
Free medical care in these villages is indeed a cause for celebration, and Bwelle with his wide smile and boundless energy is more than happy to join in the fun.
The next morning, the team began to receive hundreds of patients.
“We take 500 people on every trip,” Bwelle said.
They come from all over the county within a 60-kilometer radius of the village, and they come on foot.
Each of these weekend clinics provides a variety of medical services.
Many people receive treatment for malaria, tuberculosis, malnutrition, diabetes, parasites, and sexually transmitted diseases.
Others may receive crutches, donated glasses, or free birth certificates — documents needed for school that many poor families simply can’t afford.
In the evenings, the brigade conducts simple operations under local anesthesia.
Operations are usually performed in a school, municipality or home building; after the procedure, patients get up and go to the postoperative area to make room for the next person.
Using a generator to light up the operating and sanitation equipment, Bwelle and his volunteers work until early Sunday morning.
This is an overwhelming pace, but the brigade’s determination is usually helped by the support of village musicians.
“They beat the drums all night to keep us awake and working,” Bwelle said.
On Sunday, the members of the brigade go back to the city, tired, but proud of their work.
This group, consisting of Cameroonian doctors and foreign medical students, has conducted 700 free surgeries over the past year, and they know that their help can be of great importance to those they help.
One person explained that the free hernia treatment he received would allow him to work again.
“It will change the future for me and my family,” the man said.
In addition to these weekend clinical appointments and hospital work, Bwelle also works nights at private medical clinics around Yaoundé.
It is this latter work, he said, that provides 60% of the funding for his non-profit organization; the rest is covered by private donations.
“I don’t even know when he’s sleeping,” said Katie O’Malley, a second-year medical student at Drexel University in Philadelphia, a volunteer in the Bwelle group.
He is always either in the hospital or trying to make money for the organization so that it can continue these campaigns.
For future doctors and nurses like O’Malley, coming from the U.S. and Europe to join Bwell in carrying out his tasks, this is a practice opportunity they would never get at home.
“We were able to assist in surgeries where we helped remove blood stains or hold tools for Dr. Bwelle,” O’Malley said.
As a second-year student, you would never get that opportunity in America.
Volunteer students usually pay for their own travel to Cameroon, often arriving with donated medication.
But upon arrival in Yaoundé, their food, transportation, and training are paid for by Bwelle.
“He’s a hero, no doubt,” O’Malley said.
He gives his life to this organization, and his desire to help the people of Cameroon is endless.
For Bwelle, almost constant workload is not a difficult test.
To help others live a happy life, to fulfill the promise given to his father is what brings him great joy.
“I’m so happy when I do this job,” Bwelle said.
- And I'm thinking about my father.
I hope he sees what I'm doing.
I do it to make people laugh, to reduce their pain.
Go to the ASCOVIME website and see what you can do to help.
