Agency "Rosbalt" deprived of the status of the media for obscene language
On October 31, the Moscow City Court decided to invalidate the license to register the agency "Rosbalt", - writes "Lenta".
Roskomnadzor insisted on depriving the agency of its media status for systematic and gross violations of the law on the media.
In the course of the trial, an unpleasant precedent was created: the court considered it possible to close the media, effectively denying the publication the right to put forward counter-arguments.
What is "Rosbalt"
CJSC Rosbalt Information Agency was established in St. Petersburg in 2000.
In the following years, the agency opened a second head office in Moscow and a number of regional divisions.
The agency also has representative offices in the countries of the former USSR.
Since 2001, Rosbalt has developed and functioned as a federal information and analytical agency.
By the mid-2000s, the agency was on the list of the most recognizable private Internet media in Russia.
At the same time, Rosbalt has always occupied a rather specific niche: the core of the agency’s exclusive publications were (and still are) notes with reference to sources in law enforcement agencies.
Talks about the closeness of the publication to the power structures continued throughout the existence of the agency.
In addition to the fact that Rosbalt had an extensive database of sources in various departments, in favor of such assumptions said that the project was headed by Natalia Chaplina - the wife of Viktor Cherkesov.
At the same time, Chaplina’s role in the leadership of Rosbalt is not completely clear: she is most often called the “project manager”.
The general director of the agency is Larisa Afonina, the editor-in-chief is Nikolay Ulyanov.
Recently, Rosbalt did not appear in the ratings of the federal media - neither by citation nor by audience.
In October, the agency took the 25th place in the rating of visits to Russian media sites according to LiveInternet.
According to the same LiveInternet, the average daily audience of the site rosbalt.ru is about 150 thousand unique visitors (and up to 500 thousand views), monthly - about three million unique visitors.
Among the most popular materials for the past five months are notes about the Kremlin’s helplessness in relations with Ukraine, the death of the soloist of the group “King and Jester”, pogroms in the capital Biryulev.
The conflict between Rosbalt and Roskomnadzor began in July 2013, when amendments to the law on the media came into force, prohibiting journalists from obscene language.
The agency found banned vocabulary in two videos published on the agency's website ("Jigit from Krasnodar" and "Pussy Riot desecrated the oil rigs").
Further sides are described differently.
Roskomnadzor, on the basis of the discovered video materials, accused Rosbalt of gross and systematic violation of the law on the media and appealed to the court with a request to withdraw the license from the agency.
In "Rosbalt" stated that the claims of the Agency are illegal: firstly, the videos were not editorial materials, secondly, the native words in them were disguised, and, thirdly, immediately after the warning, the videos were removed from the site.
Representatives of the agency appealed Roskomnadzor’s claims in the justice of the peace – and when the Moscow City Court accepted Roskomnadzor’s claim on October 22, 2013, the consideration of these complaints was still ongoing.
However, on the 25th, the justice of the peace made a decision not in favor of Rosbalt: editor-in-chief Nikolai Ulyanov was found guilty of violating the code of administrative offenses and fined 20 thousand rubles - 10 thousand for each video.
Obviously, this predetermined the outcome of the hearing in the Moscow City Court - if we abandon the idea that the outcome could have been predetermined even earlier.
On October 31, the court decided to invalidate the Rosbalt registration certificate, effectively depriving the agency of its media status.
It cannot be said that Rosbalt remained alone during this confrontation.
The Agency was supported by the deputies of the State Duma (the statement to the head of Roskomnadzor Alexander Zharov on October 10 was signed by 26 deputies; the document itself was submitted at the initiative of the Communist Party).
The head of the Union of Journalists of Russia Vsevolod Bogdanov, the chairman of the Moscow Union of Journalists Pavel Gusev and the head of the presidential Human Rights Council Mikhail Fedotov said about the illegality of the closure of the publication.
Moreover, according to Bogdanov, the leadership of Roskomnadzor even provided him with some guarantees that the case will not come to the revocation of the license.
The trial of Rosbalt has shown that it is safer for the media in Russia to be under whose jurisdiction today – a big question.
