Speaking via video link at an open government conference in London, Mr Kerry said: “There is no doubt that the president and I, as well as other members of the government, have actually taken some of the things that are happening on autopilot, because that possibility already existed – both during World War II and during the very difficult years of the Cold War and, of course, 9/11.”
He then became the first senior member of the U.S. government to admit that U.S. espionage had gone too far, but stressed that no one’s rights had been violated.
He said: “In some cases it has gone too far.
And the president is determined to shed light on this issue and explain himself to the people, and is now conducting a thorough analysis to ensure that no one has a sense of abuse.
I assure you, there is no abuse of innocent people in this process.”
Mr. Kerry insisted, however, that the NSA was acting out of good faith and that his surveillance operations had saved many lives.
He added: “We are working in a new world where people are ready to blow themselves up.
There is radical extremism in the world, reckless and determined to kill people, blow people up and attack governments.
And if you were able to intercept it, stop it before it happens?
We actually prevented plane crashes, building explosions and killing people because we were able to learn about these plans in advance.”
Meanwhile, U.S. lawmakers will head to Europe to help resolve issues related to alleged U.S. spying abroad and convince Europeans to continue joint counterterrorism measures with the U.S., the chairman of the Senate Subcommittee on European Affairs said on Thursday.
Connecticut Senator Chris Murphy said he spoke with members of the European Parliament and others this week and is concerned about their threats to stop participating in anti-terrorism organizations because of frustration over surveillance by the National Security Agency.
“It is really important for the national security interests of the United States that Europeans remain our supporters in our common anti-terrorism efforts,” Democrat Murphy, who serves as the first term and chairs the Senate Foreign Relations Subcommittee on European Affairs, said in an interview from Washington.
“And I’m going to Europe to let them know that we must continue to cooperate in the fight against terrorism, despite their anger at these NSA programs.”
The news that the NSA has collected millions of phone records in Europe has worsened relations with some U.S. allies, though the agency chief said this week that they were inaccurate and reflected a misunderstanding of the metadata NATO allies were collecting and sharing with the U.S.
Other revelations cited documents released by Snowden that showed the NSA was monitoring German Chancellor Angela Merkel’s mobile phone, as well as the phones of some 34 other world leaders.
Director of National Intelligence James Clapper defended spying on allies as necessary and said it was commonplace on both sides.
Amid the uproar, Murphy said his office was organizing a congressional trip expected to take place this year and that he hoped the delegation would include members of both parties and both chambers.
The names of the other participating lawmakers are due to be announced in the coming days.
According to him, the program of the trip is still at the stage of development.
Although Murphy stated that the purpose of the trip was to promote better relations, he said that some degree of “brutality from the best motives” would also be manifested.
He said European leaders should be honest with their people about what spying programs they themselves have used over the years.
“While we can change our surveillance programs to better protect the rights of Europeans, they must also accept the fact that we are not the only ones engaged in intelligence activities,” Murphy said.
Meanwhile, Mr. Kerry is due to head to the Middle East and Poland this weekend to address issues of hostility toward U.S. strategy in Syria, Egypt and Iran, as well as U.S. intelligence activities.
In the new composition of public supervisory commissions will increase the influence of prison officers
Today, the Council of the Public Chamber (OP) can approve new composition of public observation commissions (ONC) in 43 regions of Russia.
If the option put to the vote is adopted, the lobbyists of the security forces will increase their influence.
ONCs are social structures that control the conditions of detention in places of deprivation of liberty.
The cases of Sergei Magnitsky and Leonid Razvozjaev, the unrest in the colony of Cope - it is through the ONC that most resonant incidents behind bars are publicized.
There is a struggle for control of the ONC between human rights defenders and lobbyists of the security forces.
At the meeting of the OP working group on the formation of the ONC, I proposed to make the selection criterion the experience of human rights activities.
"He was not accepted, and formed lists, without developing criteria," - says Valery Borshchev.
Borschev is the current chairman of the Moscow monitoring commission and the Association of Independent Observers, an all-Russian structure of human rights defenders dealing with prison issues.
As a State Duma deputy from Yabloko, he developed a law regulating the activities of the ONC.
The OP Council must vote for the composition of the ONC in 43 regions of the country.
Fewer than a thousand people apply for 1,800 vacancies, and in Ingushetia and Kabardino-Balkaria, competitions could not be organized due to the lack of candidates.
OP promises to organize a pre-selection for vacant seats.
The Moscow ONC is one of the few commissions with a competition, despite the fact that the new composition will have 40 participants instead of 20.
According to Borshchev, in the current composition of the Metropolitan Commission, 11 human rights defenders and 9 security forces, and in the version that is voted on in the OP, the ratio changes by 17 to 23.
At the same time, 30 human rights defenders wanted to get to the capital commission.
But a representative of the "Fighting Brotherhood" Vyacheslav Kalinin can re-enter the new composition.
He was a member of the ONC for three years, but never visited the prisoners.
Borschev believes that the security forces, having appointed their chairman of the ONC, will be able to make the work of human rights defenders intolerable, so human rights defenders do not exclude a collective withdrawal from the commission.
In their opinion, the promotion of security forces is coordinated by the member of the ONC Anton Tsvetkov, who heads the "Officers of Russia" - an organization that defends the interests of law enforcement agencies.
"I do not eat babies on the back of the truck," Anton Tsvetkov told RBC daily.
He denies lobbying for the promotion of any lists and says he has no intention of preventing human rights defenders from visiting arrested opposition figures.
According to Tsvetkov, he was not even interested in what list is now voted in the OP.
He considers the publication of Borschev’s information a form of pressure.
The possible success of human rights defenders is the planned change of leadership of the Chelyabinsk ONC.
Its former leaders will be removed due to last year's kopeck riots.
In the Public Chamber came to the conclusion that the leadership of the local commission ignored the problems of prisoners.
But the ONC Rostov-on-Don can move from human rights defenders to security forces.
The human rights chairman of the local commission disappeared from the new lists, but turned out to be one of his opponents, despite the fact that in May 2013 the Federal Public Chamber expelled him for unethical behavior.
Borschev considers the lists of the Moscow and Rostov commissions “a revenge for Kopeysk”.
The revelations of Nadezhda Tolokonnikova did not affect the ONC of Mordovia, which is considered a “force”: only one human rights activist wanted to get into the new composition, and she did not even accept documents for the competition.
OP Council member Nikolai Svanidze told RBC daily that he voted against the proposed list, as he is outraged by the situation in Moscow and Rostov-on-Don.
He sent his position to other members of the council.
His colleague on OP Pavel Gusev says that he voted for, because he likes the proposed Moscow list.
The compilation of the lists of the ONC was coordinated by the Deputy Secretary of the OP Vladislav Grib, who is also an employee of the Research Institute of the Federal Penitentiary Service.
Grib told RBC daily that he does not consider it right to divide candidates into human rights defenders and security forces and does not agree that the chairmen of the commissions have enough powers to interfere with the work of its members.
The Mushroom does not undertake to predict the results of the vote of the OP Council.
If the proposed list is rejected today, an amended version will be put to the vote in the coming days.
Australian Woman Appeals Against Thai Prison Sentence
A 21-year-old woman from Sydney, sentenced to 15 days in prison on Phuket Island for falsely claiming she was attacked by a taxi driver, appealed the sentence and was released on bail.
Stevie Rochelle Bamford was initially found guilty on June 15 by a Phuket provincial court of filing a false claim after Thai police reported that a local taxi driver carried out the attack on the night of Sunday, June 10, while two other men were holding her.
However, CCTV footage later revealed that she had safely returned to her hotel after breaking up with her Australian boyfriend.
Phuket police interrogated Bamford for two days before she admitted to fabricating the story.
Before the trial, she was held in local police cells.
Bamford was sentenced to a 15-day prison term at a general-regime detention center on the outskirts of Phuket, not an adult women's prison.
She is the daughter of former Australian League player Peter Tanks, who turned to the Foreign Office in Canberra for help for his daughter.
Tanks told the Sydney Sunday Telegraph that the whole family was "extremely concerned" about her daughter's well-being and was waiting for her return to Australia.
“Obviously it was an unsettling time, but we hope she gets home safely as soon as possible,” Tanks said.
Bamford appealed her conviction and was released on bail of 50,000 baht.
According to reports in Australia, she is currently spending her vacation in the resort area of Krabi in southern Thailand.
Legal sources in Thailand said Bamford is currently representing a local lawyer in Phuket, but warned that the appeal could lead to a court extending her sentence to up to two years and forcing her to serve time in an adult prison.
However, after the recent murder of Australian travel agent Michelle Smith in Phuket, Thailand may also seek to restore its undermined tourist image, which will lead to an acquittal.
